<div id="subtree-container" class="subtree-container"><div class="aea2d7dde423afa7ad9351a0886150a8-scss b51b00c1669ad99a1c607cd1e77c2824-scss" style="inset: 569px 35px 0px 0px; justify-content: flex-end;"><div class="afeebf1df237d4103108ba40799802d6-scss"><div class="c13443431e58facf06f9d12490b92a82-scss" style="width: 90vw; max-width: 8.5in;"><div class="_0df5ec6b9902d7d22ccfa3ebb4f35211-scss">Automated Takeoff â€“ Modelled Elements</div><div class="e5e059a27f4c194020f0d961a3cb5989-scss" dir="auto"><div class="fr-view"><p id="isPasted">This approach involves modeling the rebar within dedicated authoring software platforms, as illustrated by Figure 06.&nbsp;</p>
    <p>This process enables the calculation of rebar lengths and volumes based on the modeled geometry, thus determining the final weight by applying ratios to these dimensions, according to each material, as detailed by the equation below.</p>
    <p style="margin-top:0in;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:.5in;text-align:justify;text-indent:0in;line-height:125%;font-size:15px;font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif;" id="isPasted"><img src="https://private.lodplanner.com/projects/11696/plan-content/1700585051992_8d797e61-46f5-4faa-b092-7995a939934f.png?Expires=1769302543&amp;Signature=ZEAW4TMYJC9eXMxyWDL94rGMS34lbDFOLv8kviUOFRQzX154zC5es44MG6Xu9NOCa0UagOv~qbfRjmSEy2O5cLq6tBDn5uiB4ieRiZPPXdf0l070KQ2EpmMzaxNeJn0sWm0h5dRS-wVmIiYXtv0GDFv63uLGYX5W4PovZ9xWIOVlPKO9lC1ZQH~awGFeDoGT3DIOXyDM-4HCLOEwBMP8U9fgRZwdMMfe2yG8wMFFedXWTBGiT4w0ysjbetQRVbJvZhZdWe7WZqoKA1sm6~-V~ElwtasQeEnL3zxcnrLfXa7QBZQ~gzw1yD4YsfwYSWmDSfjKnsaC0~s4wQerGetJng__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAJRIVA6WNZT4BZJPQ" style="width: 618px;" class="fr-fic fr-dib"></p>
    <p>While this approach provides accurate rebar quantities, it's important to acknowledge that it requires a substantial amount of effort and energy.&nbsp;</p>
    <p>Therefore, it's only recommended to be employed when required by the EIR or conducted by the reinforcement contractor for their own purposes.</p>
